@startuml 05_Application_Signals_SLO_Flow
!theme aws-orange
title CloudWatch Application Signals — SLO Data Flow\n<size:12>Blog: Amazon CloudWatch Application Signals adds new SLO capabilities (2026-03-13)</size>

skinparam activity {
    BackgroundColor #FFF3E0
    BorderColor #E65100
}

|Fargate Services|
start
:Spring Boot app handles\nHTTP request;
:ADOT Java agent auto-instruments\nrequest (latency, status, trace);
:TenantContextSpanProcessor\nadds **tenant.id** from X-Tenant-Id;
:OTLP gRPC → localhost:4317\n(ADOT Collector sidecar);

|ADOT Collector|
:Receives OTLP telemetry;
fork
    :Export **traces** → X-Ray;
fork again
    :Export **metrics** → CloudWatch;
fork again
    :Export **service telemetry**\n→ Application Signals;
end fork

|Application Signals|
:Auto-discover service\n(service.name + namespace);
:Aggregate per-operation metrics\n(GET /claims, POST /claims, etc.);
:Feed into **SLO Engine**;

if (SLO breached?) then (yes)
    :Calculate error budget\nburn rate;
    if (Fast burn > 14.4x/1h?) then (yes)
        :Fire CloudWatch Alarm\n→ SNS → email/Slack;
        :Mark SLO as **Breached**;
    else (no)
        if (Slow burn > 6x/6h?) then (yes)
            :Fire warning alarm;
            :Mark SLO as **At Risk**;
        else (no)
            :SLO **Healthy**;
        endif
    endif
else (no)
    :SLO **Healthy**\nError budget intact;
endif

|Blog Feature: Performance Reports|
:Aggregate daily/weekly/monthly\nSLO compliance data;
:Generate calendar-aligned\nPerformance Report;
:Available in Console\n(Week 1+);

|Blog Feature: SLO Recommendations|
:After 30 days of metrics;
:Analyze P99 latency + error rates;
:Suggest data-driven SLO targets;
:One-click accept → create SLO;

stop

@enduml
